## Overview

This project was a ground-up rebuild of a retail e-commerce platform that had outgrown its original architecture. The client had been patching their Magento 1 installation for years, but the compounding technical debt had reached a tipping point where the cost of maintenance exceeded the cost of rebuilding.

## The Challenge

The existing platform suffered from several interconnected problems. Server-side rendering on aging infrastructure meant every page request was slow. The templating system made frontend changes fragile — a CSS update could break checkout on certain browsers. And the lack of a proper staging environment meant the team was effectively testing in production.

Beyond the technical issues, the business had evolved. The marketing team wanted A/B testing, personalized product recommendations, and the ability to run flash sales without engineering involvement. None of that was feasible on the existing stack.

## Approach

I started with a two-week discovery phase, auditing the existing codebase, interviewing stakeholders, and mapping out the critical user journeys. This surfaced a few non-obvious constraints: the client had a custom loyalty program with complex pricing rules that needed to be preserved exactly, and their warehouse management system had a brittle API integration that had to be maintained throughout the migration.

The architecture decision to go headless was straightforward given the requirements, but the choice of Shopify Plus as the commerce backend was deliberate. The client's team was small and needed a platform they could operate without deep technical expertise. Shopify Plus gave them that while still exposing the APIs needed for a custom frontend.

## Implementation

The frontend was built as a Next.js application with static generation for product and category pages, and incremental static regeneration to keep inventory data fresh without full rebuilds. The design system was built in Tailwind CSS with a component library that the marketing team could use to build landing pages independently.

The loyalty program integration was the most complex piece. I built a middleware layer that translated between the new Shopify order model and the legacy loyalty system's API, handling edge cases like split shipments and partial refunds that the original integration had never properly addressed.

## Results

The rebuild launched on schedule after four months of development. The performance improvements were immediate and measurable, but the longer-term impact was the change in how the team worked. Deployments went from anxiety-inducing events to routine operations, and the marketing team gained the autonomy they needed to run campaigns without engineering bottlenecks.
